      <p style="font-family: var(--font-ui); font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--color-ink-muted); border-left: 3px solid var(--color-accent); padding: var(--space-3) var(--space-4); background: var(--color-bg-subtle); margin-bottom: var(--space-8);">
        <strong>Heads up.</strong> This page is the working template. For any individual assignment we send you the same terms by email with the specifics filled in (working title, deadline, fee, deliverables). Both sides reply <em>"agreed"</em> and that becomes the binding agreement for that piece. Nothing here replaces our <a href="/ethics/">ethics policy</a>, <a href="/standards/">editorial standards</a>, or <a href="/corrections/">corrections policy</a> — those govern us regardless of what any single contract says.
      </p>

      <h2 id="scope">Scope</h2>
      <p>This contract covers a single piece of work, called the <strong>Assignment</strong>, that you produce for {{ site.title }}. It does not make you an employee. It does not give us first refusal on your future work. It does not stop you writing for anyone else, on any topic, before, during, or after this Assignment.</p>

      <h2 id="parties">Parties</h2>
      <p>The two parties are:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>{{ site.title }}</strong> ("we", "us") — the publisher.</li>
        <li><strong>You</strong> — the contributor named in the Assignment email.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 id="assignment">The assignment</h2>
      <p>The Assignment email will state, in writing:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>A working title or topic.</li>
        <li>Approximate length (in words) and format (article, note, feature, review, etc.).</li>
        <li>The agreed deadline.</li>
        <li>The fee, if any (see <a href="#payment">Payment</a>).</li>
        <li>Any constraints — deliverables, sources we expect, photographs or graphics required.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>If the scope changes substantially after you start, either side can ask to renegotiate. If we cannot agree, the <a href="#kill-fee">kill fee</a> applies.</p>

      <h2 id="editorial-control">Editorial control</h2>
      <p>We have final editorial control over what we publish under our masthead. That means we can:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Edit for clarity, length, accuracy, and house style.</li>
        <li>Ask you for revisions, additional reporting, or further sourcing.</li>
        <li>Decline to publish, with a kill fee, if the piece does not meet our standards or if events overtake it.</li>
        <li>Choose the headline, deck, art, and timing of publication.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>What we will not do:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Change the substantive argument of your piece without your sign-off.</li>
        <li>Add quotes, sources, or claims you did not write.</li>
        <li>Publish under your byline anything you have explicitly asked us to remove.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 id="originality">Originality and rights</h2>
      <p>You confirm that the work is yours. Specifically:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>You wrote it (or, where stated, co-wrote it with named collaborators).</li>
        <li>It is original and not previously published anywhere else, including your own newsletter, blog, or social feed, unless we agree in writing it is a republication.</li>
        <li>It does not knowingly infringe anyone's copyright, trademark, privacy, or right of publicity.</li>
        <li>Any quotations, images, or data you've used are either licensed, in the public domain, or covered by fair use / fair dealing as applicable in your jurisdiction.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 id="license">License granted to us</h2>
      <p>You grant {{ site.title }} a <strong>non-exclusive, perpetual, worldwide, royalty-free license</strong> to:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Publish the Assignment on our site, in our RSS feeds, in our newsletters, and in our archives.</li>
        <li>Republish, syndicate, or excerpt it under our standard <a href="/license/">CC BY-NC-ND 4.0</a> terms.</li>
        <li>Translate it, with a note crediting the translator.</li>
        <li>Include it in best-of collections, anthologies, and books drawn from the site, with credit and a notification to you.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>"Non-exclusive" is the key word. <strong>You can republish the same piece anywhere else after we publish it</strong>, including on your own site, in your own newsletter, in another magazine, or in a book. We ask only that you wait <strong>30 days</strong> after our publication before republishing elsewhere, and that you note <em>"originally published in {{ site.title }}"</em> with a link to our version when you do.</p>

      <h2 id="you-keep">What you keep</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>The copyright. The piece is yours; we have a license, not ownership.</li>
        <li>The right to develop the same ideas in different work for other publishers.</li>
        <li>The right to use the piece in your portfolio, in pitches, and in academic or grant submissions.</li>
        <li>The right to be credited by name on every copy of the piece we publish or syndicate.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 id="payment">Payment</h2>
      <p>Fees, when offered, are stated in the Assignment email. Some pieces are paid; many are not. We are upfront about which is which before you commit. We do not pay in "exposure", in promises, or in future considerations.</p>
      <p>If a fee is agreed:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>We pay within <strong>30 days of publication</strong> by your preferred method (bank transfer, Stripe, or check).</li>
        <li>If we accept the piece but delay publication beyond 90 days for our own reasons, we pay anyway.</li>
        <li>You are responsible for any taxes on the fee in your jurisdiction.</li>
        <li>Reasonable, pre-approved expenses (records-request fees, archive subscriptions, travel) are reimbursed against receipts.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>If no fee is agreed, the Assignment is volunteer / pro-bono and there is no payment obligation on either side.</p>

      <h2 id="corrections">Corrections and retractions</h2>
      <p>If we make a factual error, we correct it, in line with our <a href="/corrections/">corrections policy</a>. We will:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Tell you before we publish a correction to your piece.</li>
        <li>Add a dated correction note at the bottom of the article and update the body.</li>
        <li>Retract a piece, with a public note, if a fact at its core turns out to be wrong.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>If you discover an error in your own work after publication, please tell us. We will not punish you for surfacing problems.</p>

      <h2 id="takedown">Takedown and unpublishing</h2>
      <p>We do not unpublish work to please subjects, advertisers, or critics. We will only unpublish a piece if:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>It contains a factual error that cannot be corrected by editing or annotation.</li>
        <li>It contains material we are legally compelled to remove.</li>
        <li>It exposes a source, victim, or bystander to verifiable, ongoing harm and a correction is insufficient.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>If you ask us to unpublish your own piece because of a personal or professional change of heart, we will discuss it. We will not promise in advance to do so. The default is preservation: the historical record is part of the value of the site.</p>

      <h2 id="kill-fee">Kill fee</h2>
      <p>If we commission a piece (with a fee) and then choose not to publish it, you receive a <strong>kill fee equal to 50% of the agreed fee</strong>, and you keep all rights — including the right to sell the piece elsewhere immediately, with no waiting period.</p>
      <p>If you withdraw a commissioned piece before delivery, no kill fee is owed and we have no obligation to publish.</p>

      <h2 id="confidentiality">Confidentiality</h2>
      <p>Anything you tell us about your sources stays with us. We will not name a confidential source on the page, in our records, or in conversation with anyone outside the editorial chain, without your written sign-off.</p>
      <p>Conversely, we ask that you keep our internal editorial discussions (drafts, reviews, decisions about other pieces or contributors) confidential while the assignment is in progress.</p>

      <h2 id="sources">Sources and verification</h2>
      <p>You agree to:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Provide a list of sources for every factual claim, on request, before publication.</li>
        <li>Cooperate with our <a href="/volunteer/#fact-checker">fact-checking</a> process, including answering follow-up questions and providing documents where reasonable.</li>
        <li>Disclose any conflicts of interest — financial, personal, professional — with the subjects of your reporting.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 id="warranties">Warranties</h2>
      <p>You warrant that:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>The work is original, as defined in <a href="#originality">Originality and rights</a>.</li>
        <li>You have the legal right to grant us the license described above.</li>
        <li>The work does not knowingly defame any identifiable person or entity, breach any non-disclosure agreement you are bound by, or violate any law.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>We warrant that:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>We will not publish you under terms different from those in the Assignment email and this contract.</li>
        <li>We will credit you, pay any agreed fee on time, and apply our published <a href="/standards/">editorial standards</a> evenly.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 id="liability">Liability</h2>
      <p>If a third party sues us over your piece, you and we will cooperate. You are liable for damages caused by a breach of your warranties (e.g. you plagiarized, or you fabricated a quote). We are liable for damages caused by our own editorial choices (e.g. we added a claim during editing without your sign-off).</p>
      <p>Neither side is liable to the other for indirect, consequential, or speculative damages — lost income, lost opportunity, reputational harm beyond what flows directly from the breach.</p>

      <h2 id="term">Term and termination</h2>
      <p>This contract starts when both sides reply <em>"agreed"</em> to the Assignment email and ends when:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>The piece is published and any fee paid; or</li>
        <li>We choose not to publish and pay the kill fee; or</li>
        <li>You withdraw before delivery.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>The license you grant us survives termination. So do the warranties, the corrections obligations, and the confidentiality obligations on both sides.</p>

      <h2 id="disputes">Disputes</h2>
      <p>If we disagree about something:</p>
      <ol>
        <li><strong>Talk first.</strong> A direct conversation, by email or call, with the editor handling your piece.</li>
        <li><strong>Escalate.</strong> If unresolved, raise it with the editor-in-chief in writing.</li>
        <li><strong>Mediation.</strong> If still unresolved, both sides agree to attempt mediation through a mutually agreed third party before any legal action.</li>
        <li><strong>Jurisdiction.</strong> Any legal proceedings are governed by the laws of the jurisdiction where {{ site.title }} is registered, stated in the Assignment email.</li>
      </ol>

      <h2 id="sign">How to sign</h2>
      <p>You don't sign this page. The page is the template. The contract is formed when:</p>
      <ol>
        <li>We send you an Assignment email referring to this page and stating the specifics (title, length, deadline, fee).</li>
        <li>You reply <em>"agreed"</em> (or words to that effect) within the time window stated in our email.</li>
      </ol>
      <p>Keep that email exchange. It is the record of your contract with us.</p>

